  <h2>Why Nutrition Matters</h2>
  <p>
    The pet food market is overwhelming — thousands of products making competing claims, with ingredient lists that are hard to evaluate. Many pet owners are making well-intentioned choices that don't match their specific pet's needs. A personalized nutritional assessment helps cut through the noise.
  </p>
  <p>
    At All About Pets, we approach nutrition as part of comprehensive care. We review your pet's current diet at wellness visits and provide guidance when health conditions, life stage changes, or weight concerns arise.
  </p>

  <h2>What We Assess</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Dietary composition</strong> — reviewing your pet's current food for caloric density, macronutrient balance, and ingredient quality</li>
    <li><strong>Life stage nutrition</strong> — puppies and kittens, adults, seniors, and pregnant or nursing animals all have distinct nutritional requirements</li>
    <li><strong>Breed-specific considerations</strong> — some breeds have known predispositions to food sensitivities, joint disease, or metabolic conditions that diet can help manage</li>
    <li><strong>Feeding schedules and portion sizes</strong> — how often and how much matters as much as what's in the bowl</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Weight Management</h2>
  <p>
    Obesity is one of the most common and most preventable health problems in pets. Excess weight contributes to arthritis, diabetes, heart disease, respiratory issues, and shortened lifespan. Conversely, underweight animals face their own set of risks.
  </p>
  <p>
    We assess your pet's body condition score (BCS) at every visit and work with you to develop a realistic, sustainable plan if weight adjustment is needed — including specific food recommendations and activity guidance.
  </p>

  <h2>Food Allergies and Sensitivities</h2>
  <p>
    Skin issues, chronic ear infections, gastrointestinal upset, and coat problems can all be signs of a food sensitivity or allergy. We can help identify potential triggers and guide you through an elimination diet if needed, recommending appropriate hypoallergenic or limited-ingredient options.
  </p>

